    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm running a linear regression on some housing price data and the residuals don't look normal at all. the distribution is pretty skewed. what's the best way to handle this if i want to keep using a linear model?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A skewed residual distribution, a classic problem, is often best handled by transforming your data, or perhaps just the target variable itself, to make it more symmetrical. You can try a log transformation ($\\log(Y)$) or a square root transformation ($\\sqrt{Y}$) on the housing prices before running your linear regression. Sometimes, if the skew is severe, a Box-Cox transformation can be a good go-to, though that can be a bit more involved. Remember, transforming the data is just trying to make the underlying relationship look more like a straight line to the model, which is what we want.",
