    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i tried the log transformation but the residuals are still acting weird. there are these really big outliers that just seem to pop up randomly and mess with the fit. is there a way to detect them more formally or just deal with them if they're part of the actual data?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Outliers, especially those that pop up randomly like those, are the bane of any model, especially when you're trying to keep the linear structure intact. You can detect them formally using methods like the **Grubbs' test** or by looking at **Cook's distance** and **Leverage**. If a point has a high Cook's distance, it means that point is having a disproportionate influence on the regression coefficients, which is exactly what you want to watch out for. It's a big deal, because if you don't handle them, they can drag your whole model off course, making it look like a poorly-trained, poorly-motivated collection of noisy data.",
      "source": "target",
